    mechanism:
      "**Copper** is an essential trace mineral and structural / catalytic cofactor in approximately a dozen mammalian enzymes spanning oxidative metabolism, connective tissue synthesis, neurotransmitter production, antioxidant defense, and iron metabolism. The mineral is unusual in that **adult deficiency from inadequate dietary intake is rare** in developed populations consuming any reasonable diet — but **functional deficiency from chronic high-zinc supplementation is common and clinically significant**. The principal modern issue with copper is the iatrogenic deficiency induced by users supplementing zinc above 40mg daily without copper repletion, not raw dietary inadequacy. **Mechanism — the key copper enzymes**: (1) **Ceruloplasmin** — the principal circulating copper-binding protein; carries copper in plasma; required for iron oxidation (ferroxidase activity) and iron incorporation into transferrin for tissue delivery. Copper deficiency produces iron-deficiency-like anemia despite adequate iron stores because ceruloplasmin cannot mobilize iron from tissue stores. (2) **Cytochrome c oxidase** — terminal enzyme in the mitochondrial electron transport chain; copper-dependent; deficiency impairs cellular ATP production. (3) **Lysyl oxidase** — cross-links collagen and elastin in connective tissue; copper deficiency produces vascular fragility, joint laxity, and impaired wound healing. (4) **Cu/Zn superoxide dismutase (SOD1)** — major cellular antioxidant; copper-dependent. (5) **Dopamine beta-hydroxylase** — converts dopamine to norepinephrine; copper deficiency affects catecholamine balance. (6) **Tyrosinase** — melanin synthesis; deficiency produces hypopigmentation. (7) **Peptidylglycine alpha-amidating monooxygenase (PAM)** — required for amidation of multiple peptide hormones. **Mechanism — the zinc-copper antagonism (the central modern issue)**: zinc and copper share intestinal absorption pathways via metallothionein-1 and ZIP transporters. High zinc intake (above ~40mg daily long-term) upregulates intestinal metallothionein, which preferentially binds copper and traps it in enterocytes, where it is excreted via fecal sloughing. Result: chronic high-zinc supplementation produces iatrogenic copper deficiency over months to years. The clinical presentation is anemia (despite adequate iron), neutropenia, peripheral neuropathy, ataxia, and impaired immune function. The fix is straightforward: **users supplementing zinc above 25mg daily long-term should pair with copper at approximately 15:1 zinc:copper ratio** (the BATCH37 Zinc tile pre-positioned this; this tile closes the cross-reference). For example: 25mg zinc + 1.5-2mg copper. This ratio is well-established and prevents iatrogenic copper deficiency without producing copper toxicity at the supplemental doses involved. **Mechanism — copper toxicity context**: copper has a relatively narrow therapeutic window. Acute toxicity from supplemental forms occurs above 10mg daily over time; chronic toxicity (Wilson's disease in genetically susceptible individuals) is a clinical condition requiring chelation therapy. The supplemental dose range relevant to zinc-copper ratio repletion (1-3mg daily) is well below toxicity thresholds. **Mechanism — bisglycinate vs gluconate vs sulfate (form-selection)**: copper bisglycinate (chelated to two glycine molecules) and copper glycinate (chelated to one glycine) offer better bioavailability and gentler GI tolerance than copper gluconate or copper sulfate. Copper sulfate is poorly tolerated GI-wise; copper gluconate is adequate but produces more GI side effects than glycinate forms. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability ~30-40% standard forms, ~50%+ glycinate; peak plasma 2-4 hours; tissue distribution wide; excretion principally via biliary route (limited renal excretion is the basis for copper toxicity in cholestatic liver disease). **Pharmaceutical status**: copper is a dietary supplement; not a pharmaceutical; widely available in supplement formulations and as a component in zinc-copper combination products.",
