    mechanism:
      "**Inositol** is a six-carbon cyclic polyol (cyclohexanehexol) classified as a vitamin-like compound — endogenously synthesized from glucose but at quantities often inadequate for therapeutic effects, making dietary or supplemental inositol functionally relevant. Nine stereoisomers exist; the two with substantial biological activity in human metabolism are **myo-inositol (MI)** and **D-chiro-inositol (DCI)**, which serve as second messengers in insulin signaling and other receptor pathways. **Mechanism — inositol phosphoglycan second messengers (the foundational mechanism)**: when insulin binds its receptor, downstream signaling involves multiple second messenger systems including the inositol phosphoglycan (IPG) pathway. **Myo-inositol-derived IPG (MI-IPG)** activates pyruvate dehydrogenase phosphatase, supporting glucose oxidation and ATP production. **D-chiro-inositol-derived IPG (DCI-IPG)** supports glycogen synthesis via glycogen synthase activation. The two pathways operate in parallel and tissue-specifically — different tissues have different myo:D-chiro ratios depending on metabolic role. Insulin resistance (notably PCOS and metabolic syndrome) is associated with disrupted IPG signaling and altered tissue myo:D-chiro ratios, providing the mechanistic basis for inositol supplementation in these contexts. **Mechanism — the 40:1 myo:D-chiro ratio (the central form-selection question)**: ovarian tissue normally maintains a high myo-inositol:D-chiro-inositol ratio (~100:1) which supports oocyte quality and follicular development. In PCOS, ovarian D-chiro-inositol levels are paradoxically elevated relative to myo-inositol (the 'ovarian DCI paradox'), disrupting the ratio and contributing to ovulatory dysfunction. Combined supplementation at **40:1 myo:D-chiro ratio (typically 2g myo + 50mg D-chiro daily)** is the protocol established by Italian fertility researchers (Unfer, Carlomagno, others) and now standard in PCOS practice. The ratio matters substantially — myo-only supplementation works but pairs less synergistically with D-chiro; D-chiro-heavy supplementation can paradoxically worsen ovarian dysfunction in some PCOS cohorts; the 40:1 ratio replicates the physiological balance and produces the most consistent clinical results. **Mechanism — PCOS clinical effects**: combined 40:1 myo:D-chiro supplementation in PCOS has demonstrated improvements in: insulin sensitivity (HOMA-IR reduction), ovulation rate (60-70% ovulation in protocols), pregnancy rates, androgen levels (free testosterone, DHEAS), lipid profile, and weight management context. The LIFT trial framework (referenced in BATCH38 Letrozole and BATCH39 Clomiphene tiles) compared Letrozole vs Clomid for PCOS ovulation induction; inositol supplementation occupies a distinct foundational lane that often precedes or supports pharmacological ovulation induction. **Mechanism — myo-only contexts (the broader use case)**: myo-inositol monotherapy at 2-4g daily has separate evidence base for: anxiety and panic disorder (12-18g daily in some trials), OCD (12-18g daily), depression adjunct, gestational diabetes prevention, metabolic syndrome insulin sensitivity, and male fertility (sperm parameter improvement). The myo-only contexts don't require D-chiro pairing — myo-inositol provides the central second messenger activity, and D-chiro pairing is specifically PCOS / ovarian-dysfunction relevant. **Mechanism — IP6 (inositol hexaphosphate, phytate)**: a separate inositol form found in plant foods and available as supplement; chelates minerals (iron, calcium, zinc) and has antioxidant / anti-cancer research themes; **NOT the form for PCOS or metabolic supplementation** — the IPG signaling activity requires unbound myo or D-chiro inositol, not the heavily phosphorylated IP6 form. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability good; rapidly absorbed; tissue distribution wide; metabolized via inositol oxygenation pathway; renal excretion. Half-life functional for tissue effects is hours. Daily dosing standard, often divided BID. **Pharmaceutical status**: inositol is a dietary supplement; not FDA-approved as pharmaceutical; sold OTC in capsule, tablet, and powder forms. Some European markets have inositol products labeled for fertility / PCOS indications but US market is supplement-tier.",
