    mechanism:
      "**Boswellia** is the genus of resin-producing trees in the Burseraceae family whose dried sap (frankincense) has been used in Ayurvedic, Unani, and traditional Chinese medicine for thousands of years for inflammatory and joint conditions. The principal medicinal species are **Boswellia serrata** (Indian frankincense, the dominant supplemental source) and **Boswellia carterii** (Somali frankincense, traditionally aromatic / spiritual use). The active constituents are a family of pentacyclic triterpene acids called **boswellic acids**, with the most pharmacologically significant being **acetyl-11-keto-beta-boswellic acid (AKBA)** — the form responsible for Boswellia's distinctive 5-lipoxygenase (5-LOX) inhibitory activity. **Mechanism — 5-LOX inhibition (the central mechanism distinguishing Boswellia)**: arachidonic acid metabolism produces inflammatory eicosanoids via two principal pathways. **Cyclooxygenase (COX-1, COX-2)** produces prostaglandins (PGE2 driving inflammation, fever, pain) — this is the NSAID mechanism (aspirin, ibuprofen, naproxen, celecoxib block COX). **5-Lipoxygenase (5-LOX)** produces leukotrienes (LTB4 driving neutrophil chemotaxis; cysteinyl leukotrienes LTC4/LTD4/LTE4 driving bronchoconstriction, vascular permeability, inflammatory tissue infiltration). NSAIDs do not address the 5-LOX pathway; this is mechanistically why NSAIDs alone often inadequately control inflammatory conditions where leukotriene-mediated pathways dominate (asthma, IBD, certain joint inflammation contexts). Boswellia's AKBA selectively inhibits 5-LOX, addressing the leukotriene arm of inflammatory eicosanoid metabolism. The mechanism is distinct from NSAID COX inhibition and complementary — Boswellia + NSAID combinations sometimes produce additive anti-inflammatory effects in clinical practice. **Mechanism — additional anti-inflammatory effects**: AKBA also inhibits human leukocyte elastase (HLE), modulates NF-kappa-B signaling, reduces TNF-alpha and IL-6 production, and inhibits matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) involved in cartilage and connective tissue breakdown. The multi-target effect explains Boswellia's broad anti-inflammatory profile beyond pure 5-LOX inhibition. **Mechanism — joint inflammation context (the principal clinical use)**: osteoarthritis (OA), rheumatoid arthritis (RA), and broader joint inflammation contexts have substantial Boswellia clinical evidence. Trials with standardized AKBA-rich extracts (5-Loxin, ApresFlex) have demonstrated joint pain reduction (WOMAC scores), improved joint function, and reduced inflammatory markers (CRP, ESR) in OA cohorts. The effect onset is typically 2-4 weeks (vs days for NSAIDs) — Boswellia is not an acute-relief intervention but a sustained anti-inflammatory strategy. **Mechanism — inflammatory bowel disease (separate evidence base)**: Boswellia has been studied in ulcerative colitis (UC) and Crohn's disease with positive trial results — the 5-LOX inhibition addresses the leukotriene-mediated inflammatory cascade central to IBD pathophysiology. Trials have demonstrated remission rates in UC comparable to mesalamine in some cohorts. The IBD evidence base is separate from joint inflammation — both legitimate, different use cases. **Mechanism — AKBA standardization (the central form-selection question)**: standard Boswellia serrata extracts are typically standardized to 65-75% boswellic acids total, with AKBA representing 1-5% of the extract. **Premium AKBA-standardized extracts (5-Loxin at 30% AKBA, ApresFlex / AKBAMax at 20%+ AKBA)** provide substantially higher AKBA content per gram, producing stronger 5-LOX inhibition and more consistent clinical response. The form-selection matters substantially — generic 'Boswellia extract' without AKBA standardization may have substantially lower bioactive content. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability of boswellic acids is poor (~5-10%); food (especially fat) substantially improves absorption; AKBA-enhanced formulations and lecithin-complexed forms further improve bioavailability; tissue accumulation in inflammatory tissue. Half-life ~6 hours; daily dosing standard, often divided BID. **Pharmaceutical status**: Boswellia is a dietary supplement; not FDA-approved as pharmaceutical; sold OTC in capsule, tablet, and combined-formula forms. Long-standing pharmacopoeia status in Ayurvedic and traditional medicine systems.",
